  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I find work experience in Investment banking in London?",
  "response": "Finding work experience in investment banking, especially in a competitive market like London, requires a strategic approach. Here are several steps to help you secure an internship or work experience in this field:\n\n1. **Research Firms:**\n   - Identify which investment banks or financial institutions you want to apply to. Common choices include large firms like Goldman Sachs, JPMorgan, Morgan Stanley, and Barclays, as well as smaller boutique banks.\n\n2. **Networking:**\n   - Use platforms like LinkedIn to connect with professionals in the industry. Reach out for informational interviews to gain insights and advice.\n   - Attend networking events, finance conferences, or university career fairs.\n\n3. **University Careers Services:**\n   - Utilize your university\u2019s career service. They often have connections with banks and might offer exclusive internship opportunities.\n   - Participate in finance-related societies or clubs at your university to enhance your network.\n\n4. **Online Job Boards:**\n   - Check job boards and websites specifically for finance jobs, such as eFinancialCareers, Indeed, Glassdoor, or LinkedIn Jobs.\n   - Look for internship programs advised by banks, which often have set deadlines.\n\n5. **Applications:**\n   - Tailor your CV and cover letter for each application, highlighting relevant skills and experiences.\n   - Prepare for online assessment tests, which are common in investment banking recruitment.\n\n6. **Internship Programs:**\n   - Apply for formal internship programs, which typically occur during summer. Many banks have structured internship programs for penultimate-year students.\n\n7. **Recruitment Agencies:**\n   - Consider reaching out to recruitment agencies specializing in finance to help find suitable placements.\n\n8. **Skills Development:**\n   - Strengthen your quantitative and analytical skills. Familiarize yourself with financial modeling and valuation techniques.\n   - Take courses or certifications (e.g., CFA Level 1, courses on financial modeling) to enhance your knowledge and appeal.\n\n9. **Cold Outreach:**\n   - If you have specific firms in mind, consider sending cold emails to HR or department heads expressing your interest in work experience or internships.\n\n10. **Referrals:**\n   - If you know someone working in the industry, ask if they can refer you to opportunities at their firm.\n\n11. **Stay Informed:**\n   - Keep up with financial news and trends, which will help you in interviews and networking conversations.\n\n12. **Be Persistent:**\n   - Rejections may happen; don\u2019t be discouraged. Continue applying, networking, and refining your approach.\n\nMake sure to prepare well for interviews and assessments. Demonstrating a strong understanding of the financial markets, possess relevant technical skills, and showcasing enthusiasm for the role will be key to securing any position in investment banking.",
